{"key":"processedPost-6539804","value":{"id":6539804,"first":6538045,"last":6543872,"when":1170868403,"utime":"02/07/07 07:13 PM","cleanedPost":"Simply do what the commercial farms do and cut the base off with a knife.<br />Small fruit size is related to substrate moisture content.&nbsp; It's easy to hydrate a substrate block during fruiting by simply pouring water around the edges so it slides down and under the substrate.&nbsp; If you pour a few tablespoons of water around the edges a couple of times a day, the substrate will readily absorb it and transfer the moisture to your fruits.&nbsp;  Cubes will benefit from a casing layer, but by no means is one necessary to get a nice flush of large fruits.<br />Yes, wax paper helps, but if humidity is already 99%, it's not necessary.<br />RR"}}